<subSubSection lastPageId="29" lastPageNumber="30" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="28.[189,334,1533,1559]" box="[189,334,1533,1559]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,334,1533,1559]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,334,1533,1559]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[189,996,1578,1605]" box="[189,996,1578,1605]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
Similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Gonçalves &amp; Grootaert &amp; Andrade &amp; Paulo &amp; Mengual, 2021" authorityName="Gonçalves &amp; Grootaert &amp; Andrade &amp; Paulo &amp; Mengual" authorityYear="2021" box="[313,600,1578,1604]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Tachydromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cantabrica" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[313,600,1578,1604]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Tachydromia cantabrica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[607,698,1579,1605]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
except for the following:
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[189,1178,1642,1703]" box="[234,298,1642,1668]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[234,298,1642,1668]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Male</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[189,1178,1642,1703]" box="[189,1178,1676,1703]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
MEASUREMENTS. Body length: 
<quantity box="[539,680,1676,1702]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="2.6" metricValueMin="2.4" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" unit="mm" value="2.5" valueMax="2.6" valueMin="2.4">2.4–2.6 mm</quantity>
(n = 5). Wing length: 
<quantity box="[942,1083,1676,1702]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="7.0" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" unit="mm" value="0.75" valueMax="0.8" valueMin="0.7">0.7–0.8 mm</quantity>
(n = 5).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[189,1398,1738,1800]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">HEAD. Ocellar tubercle glabrous, shiny black. Lateroclinate ocellars ca ½ smaller than length of postpedicel. Proclinate verticals ca ½ as long as postpedicel.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[189,1399,1837,1897]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">ANTENNA. Postpedicel lanceolate, 2 times as long as pedicel. Stylus 1.5 times as long as scape, pedicel and postpedicel combined.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[189,791,1934,1961]" box="[189,791,1934,1961]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">THORAX. Postpronotal lobe with ca 7 setae laterally.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[189,1136,1998,2025]" box="[189,1136,1998,2025]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
WING. Stalk-like portion dark brown on basal half, pale on distal half (
<figureCitation box="[1013,1123,1998,2024]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="43.[189,232,1855,1881]" captionTargetBox="[302,1292,265,1813]" captionTargetId="figure-86@43.[296,1292,265,1813]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="Fig. 20. Drawings of the tip of stenopterous wings and images obtained by scanning electron microscope (SEM) of the micropterous wings. Males are pictured in the left column, females in the right. A–B. T. ebejeri Gonçalves, Grootaert &amp; Andrade sp. nov. C–D. T. cantabrica Gonçalves, Grootaert &amp; Andrade sp. nov. E–F. T. lusitanica (Grootaert, Shamshev &amp; Andrade, 2009). G–H. T. nigrohirta Gonçalves, Grootaert &amp; Andrade sp. nov. Scale bars: A–B, D, F, H = 10 µm; C, E, G = 50 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4471759" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4471759/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 20G</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[189,1400,265,393]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
LEGS. Black, except for yellowish to brown trochanters, knees and tarsomeres 1 and 2. Fore tibia with dense ciliation of long hair-like setae (distinctively larger than maximum diameter of tibia) with curved tips. Mid tibia anteroventral apical spur with distinct apical elongation (
<figureCitation box="[1037,1134,332,358]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="42.[189,232,1823,1849]" captionTargetBox="[312,1276,265,1775]" captionTargetId="figure-104@42.[312,1276,265,1775]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="Fig. 19. Images obtained by scanning electron microscopy of the spur-like structures present on the apical portion of the male mid tibia. A. T. lusitanica (Grootaert, Shamshev &amp; Andrade, 2009). B. T. pandellei (Séguy, 1941). C. T. pieltaini (Gil Collado, 1936). D. T. ebejeri Gonçalves, Grootaert &amp; Andrade sp. nov. E–F. T. semiaptera (Gil Collado, 1923). G. T. stenoptera Gonçalves, Grootaert &amp; Andrade sp. nov. H. T. cantabrica Gonçalves, Grootaert &amp; Andrade sp. nov. I. T. nigrohirta Gonçalves, Grootaert &amp; Andrade sp. nov. J. T. apterygon Plant &amp; Deeming, 2006. Scale bars: 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4471757" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4471757/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 19I</figureCitation>
), on basal half margin with 4 short, stout, curved spinose setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[189,1399,429,490]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
TERMINALIA (
<figureCitation box="[339,426,430,457]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="29.[189,232,1511,1537]" captionTargetBox="[194,1386,877,1463]" captionTargetId="figure-267@29.[189,1398,872,1467]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="Fig. 10. Terminalia of Tachydromia nigrohirta Gonçalves, Grootaert &amp; Andrade sp. nov., holotype (RBINS). A. Right surstylus and right epandrial lamella. B. Epandrium with cerci. C. Left epandrial lamella and left surstylus. D. Right surstylus. Scale bar: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4471737" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4471737/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
). Left epandrial lamella ½ shorter than left cercus, deeply bilobed. Left surstylus 2 times as long as wide.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[188,1398,528,689]" box="[234,325,528,554]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[234,325,528,554]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Female</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[188,1398,528,689]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
Similar to male, except for following features: micropterous, wing round, brownish, bilobate, apical margin of each lobe bearing setae, posterior lobe with 1 long seta and the anterior with 3 short setae, both covered with grey microtrichia (
<figureCitation box="[572,685,629,655]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="43.[189,232,1855,1881]" captionTargetBox="[302,1292,265,1813]" captionTargetId="figure-86@43.[296,1292,265,1813]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="Fig. 20. Drawings of the tip of stenopterous wings and images obtained by scanning electron microscope (SEM) of the micropterous wings. Males are pictured in the left column, females in the right. A–B. T. ebejeri Gonçalves, Grootaert &amp; Andrade sp. nov. C–D. T. cantabrica Gonçalves, Grootaert &amp; Andrade sp. nov. E–F. T. lusitanica (Grootaert, Shamshev &amp; Andrade, 2009). G–H. T. nigrohirta Gonçalves, Grootaert &amp; Andrade sp. nov. Scale bars: A–B, D, F, H = 10 µm; C, E, G = 50 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4471759" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4471759/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 20H</figureCitation>
); legs covered with regular rows of setae; spur on mid tibia absent; cercus pale brown with grey microtrichia and setae; no longer setae on apical sternites.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
